TY  - JOUR
T1  - Equilibrium Cross Section of Returns
AU  - Gomes, Joao
AU  - Kogan, Leonid
AU  - Zhang, Lu
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/375379
DO  - 10.1086/375379
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 693
EP  - 732
VL  - 111
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We construct a dynamic general equilibrium production economy to explicitly link expected stock returns to firm characteristics such as firm size and the book?to?market ratio. Stock returns in the model are completely characterized by a conditional capital asset pricing model (CAPM). Size and book?to?market are correlated with the true conditional market beta and therefore appear to predict stock returns. The cross?sectional relations between firm characteristics and returns can subsist even after one controls for typical empirical estimates of beta. These findings suggest that the empirical success of size and book?to?market can be consistent with a single?factor conditional CAPM model.
AB  - We construct a dynamic general equilibrium production economy to explicitly link expected stock returns to firm characteristics such as firm size and the book?to?market ratio. Stock returns in the model are completely characterized by a conditional capital asset pricing model (CAPM). Size and book?to?market are correlated with the true conditional market beta and therefore appear to predict stock returns. The cross?sectional relations between firm characteristics and returns can subsist even after one controls for typical empirical estimates of beta. These findings suggest that the empirical success of size and book?to?market can be consistent with a single?factor conditional CAPM model.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/375379
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/375379
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bequests as Signals: An Explanation for the Equal Division Puzzle
AU  - Bernheim, B. Douglas
AU  - Severinov, Sergei
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/375383
DO  - 10.1086/375383
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 733
EP  - 764
VL  - 111
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In the United States, more than two?thirds of decedents with multichild families divide their estates exactly equally among their children. In contrast, gifts given before death are usually unequal. These findings challenge the validity of existing theories regarding the determination of intergenerational transfers. In this paper, we develop a theory that accounts for this puzzle based on the notion that the division of bequests provides a signal about a parent?s altruistic preferences. The theory can also explain the norm of unigeniture, which prevails in other societies.
AB  - In the United States, more than two?thirds of decedents with multichild families divide their estates exactly equally among their children. In contrast, gifts given before death are usually unequal. These findings challenge the validity of existing theories regarding the determination of intergenerational transfers. In this paper, we develop a theory that accounts for this puzzle based on the notion that the division of bequests provides a signal about a parent?s altruistic preferences. The theory can also explain the norm of unigeniture, which prevails in other societies.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/375383
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/375383
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Who Affects Whom in Daily Newspaper Markets?
AU  - George, Lisa
AU  - Waldfogel, Joel
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/375380
DO  - 10.1086/375380
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 765
EP  - 784
VL  - 111
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - When consumers share similar preferences, additional consumers will bring forth products that confer positive ?preference externalities? on others. However, if distinct groups of consumers have substantially different preferences, the groups bring forth products with more appeal to themselves and less appeal to others. We document that in their capacity as daily newspaper consumers, blacks and whites are more likely to buy daily newspapers in markets with larger black and white populations, respectively. Similar results hold for Hispanics and non?Hispanics, but not by education, income, or age. We provide evidence that product positioning underlies our results.
AB  - When consumers share similar preferences, additional consumers will bring forth products that confer positive ?preference externalities? on others. However, if distinct groups of consumers have substantially different preferences, the groups bring forth products with more appeal to themselves and less appeal to others. We document that in their capacity as daily newspaper consumers, blacks and whites are more likely to buy daily newspapers in markets with larger black and white populations, respectively. Similar results hold for Hispanics and non?Hispanics, but not by education, income, or age. We provide evidence that product positioning underlies our results.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/375380
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/375380
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bertrand and Walras Equilibria under Moral Hazard
AU  - Bennardo, Alberto
AU  - Chiappori, Pierre‐André
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/375384
DO  - 10.1086/375384
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 785
EP  - 817
VL  - 111
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We consider a simple model of competition under moral hazard with constant return technologies. We consider preferences that are not separable in effort: marginal utility of income is assumed to increase with leisure, especially for high income levels. We show that, in this context, Bertrand competition may result in positive equilibrium profit. This result holds for purely idiosyncratic shocks when only deterministic contracts are considered and extends to unrestricted contract spaces in the presence of aggregate uncertainty. Finally, these findings have important consequences on the definition of an equilibrium. We show that, in this context, a Walrasian general equilibrium à la Prescott?Townsend may fail to exist: any ?equilibrium? must involve rationing.
AB  - We consider a simple model of competition under moral hazard with constant return technologies. We consider preferences that are not separable in effort: marginal utility of income is assumed to increase with leisure, especially for high income levels. We show that, in this context, Bertrand competition may result in positive equilibrium profit. This result holds for purely idiosyncratic shocks when only deterministic contracts are considered and extends to unrestricted contract spaces in the presence of aggregate uncertainty. Finally, these findings have important consequences on the definition of an equilibrium. We show that, in this context, a Walrasian general equilibrium à la Prescott?Townsend may fail to exist: any ?equilibrium? must involve rationing.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/375384
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/375384
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

